  "meta": {
    "title": "Tara Oceans: Temperature Sorts the Epipelagic Microbiome",
    "date": "2026-07-18",
    "lesson": "The Tara Oceans expedition sequenced 7.2 terabases of metagenomic DNA from 68 sites worldwide, building a reference catalog of >40 million microbial genes. A key discovery: across the sunlit epipelagic zone, community composition is shaped primarily by temperature rather than nutrients or geography, producing a vertically stratified ocean where warm surface waters host distinct microbial guilds from the cooler mesopelagic below. Remarkably, over 73% of core functional gene abundance is shared with the human gut microbiome, suggesting universal metabolic modules recur across wildly different ecosystems. In this level, warm surface specialists and cold deep-water specialists compete along a thermocline; success depends on matching your enzyme and chemotaxis strategy to your thermal niche.",
    "citation": "Sunagawa, Coelho, Chaffron (2015). Structure and function of the global ocean microbiome. doi:10.1126/science.1261359",
    "difficulty": "normal",
    "realWorldBasis": "Tara Oceans global metagenomic survey, 243 samples, 68 locations, epi/mesopelagic"
  },
